Software Architecture & Development Outline

Project: Open-Source Nail Gel Printer
Subsystem: Master Controller (RPi 3B+)
Phase 1: OS & System Configuration

Objective: Prepare the bare-metal environment for headless operation and hardware communication.

    Flash OS: Install Raspberry Pi OS Lite (64-bit) via Raspberry Pi Imager.

    Enable Interfaces: Use raspi-config to enable SSH, I2C, SPI, and the Camera interface.

    Configure UART (Crucial): By default, the Pi uses its hardware serial pins (GPIO 14/15) for a Linux login console. You must disable the serial console but leave the serial port hardware enabled to free it up for communicating with your ESP32.

    Install Kiosk Dependencies: Install chromium-browser, xserver-xorg, and matchbox-window-manager to allow a fullscreen browser to run without a desktop environment.

Phase 2: The Backend Engine (Python & FastAPI)

Objective: Build the core logic server that handles API requests, file uploads, and hardware commands.

    Framework: FastAPI (with Uvicorn). It is modern, incredibly fast, natively asynchronous (which is great for waiting on serial data), and automatically generates API documentation.

    Key Modules to Develop:

        server.py: The main entry point, routing HTTP requests.

        upload_handler.py: Saves incoming images from the Web UI to a temporary directory.

        serial_comm.py: Uses the pyserial library to establish a 921,600 baud connection to the ESP32. Manages the TX/RX buffers and handshakes.

Phase 3: The Computer Vision Pipeline (OpenCV)

Objective: Process the uploaded image to fit the physical nail environment.

    Framework: OpenCV for Python (cv2) and NumPy.

    Pipeline Steps:

        Capture: Trigger the internal Pi Camera (using libcamera or picamera2) and capture the illuminated finger.

        Segmentation: Isolate the nail bed from the finger cradle using edge detection and color thresholding.

        Warping: Apply the 1D Sine-wave pre-distortion to the uploaded user image to account for the nail's curvature.

        Slicing & Halftoning: Convert the warped RGB image into the CMY color space. Apply a halftoning algorithm (like Floyd-Steinberg error diffusion) to convert continuous tones into pure binary dots (fire or don't fire).

        Packetizing: Pack these binary dots into the raw byte arrays expected by your ESP32 firmware.

Phase 4: The Unified Web Frontend

Objective: Build the user interfaces for both the machine and the user's personal device.

    Tech Stack: HTML/CSS/JS (Optionally a lightweight framework like Svelte or Vue to keep it snappy on the 3B+). Serve these static files directly from your FastAPI backend.

    Touchscreen View (/):

        Minimalist interface designed for a 5-inch or 7-inch DSI/HDMI touchscreen.

        Large, finger-friendly buttons: "Ready", "Align", "Print", "Cancel".

        A live video feed component showing the user their finger alignment in real-time.

    Remote Web View (/upload):

        A mobile-friendly page accessible from the user's phone via the local Wi-Fi network (e.g., http://nailprinter.local:8000).

        Image upload button, cropping tool, and a preview of how the design will look on a generic nail shape.

Phase 5: Integration & Handshake Protocol

Objective: Make the Pi and the ESP32 talk flawlessly.

    Define a strict serial protocol. For example:

        START_PRINT: Pi wakes up the ESP32.

        READY: ESP32 confirms motors are homed.

        SEND_LINE <byte_array>: Pi sends one horizontal slice of the image.

        LINE_ACK: ESP32 confirms the line was printed successfully and its buffer is ready for the next slice.